# .gitleaksignore
#
# Suppresses known false-positive secret findings so gitleaks runs clean
# against the default ruleset (this repo no longer ships a custom
# .gitleaks.toml). Every entry below is a fake/example credential living in
# test fixtures, benchmarks, docs, or planning notes -- not a real secret.
#
# Each line is a gitleaks "fingerprint". Two formats appear because gitleaks
# emits different fingerprints depending on scan mode, and we want the ignore
# list to work for all of them:
#   * git-history scans (CI gitleaks-action, go-pre-commit git mode):
#       <commit>:<file>:<rule>:<line>
#   * directory scans (gitleaks detect --no-git --source .):
#       <file>:<rule>:<line>
#
# Maintenance notes:
#   * A NEW fake secret added in a future commit produces a NEW fingerprint
#     (new commit SHA / line number) and must be added here explicitly --
#     there is no path-glob allowlisting without a .gitleaks.toml.
#   * To regenerate after intentional changes, run a gitleaks scan with
#     --report-format json and copy the "Fingerprint" values:
#       gitleaks detect --source . --report-path leaks.json --report-format json
#       gitleaks detect --no-git --source . --report-path leaks-nogit.json --report-format json

